sentence: D ividends are a distribution of a company's profits, so the more predictable its earnings, the better.
These five stocks have a five-year Earnings Stability Factor of 1 on a scale from 0 (most stable) to 99 (least stable), and their yields top the S&P 500's average 1.94% payout .
Altria Group 's ( MO ) annualized dividend of 3.9% is the highest of the quintet.
The Marlboro maker's annual profit grew 6% or more the past seven years.
Analysts expect earnings to rise 9% this year and 8% the next.
The stock is just above a 53.09 double-bottom buy point.
Paychex ( PAYX ) recently boosted its quarterly dividend by 11% to 42 cents a share for a 3.6% yield on an annual basis.
The payroll and human resources services provider saw earnings dips in 2009 and '10, but it has since come back for a five-year earnings growth rate of 6%.
Analysts see a 9% gain this year and next.
The stock is in a flat base with a 51.82 entry.
Reynolds American ( RAI ) offers a 3.4% annualized yield.
The Camel maker, which reports Tuesday before the open, has a five-year EPS growth rate of 7%.
It's seen doubling to 14% this year and 15% in '16.
Reynolds completed its Lorillard buy last month.
Shares are 5% past a 76.20 cup-with-handle entry.
Colgate-Palmolive 's ( CL ) quarterly payout of 38 cents a share works out to a 2.3% annual dividend.
Analysts expect the consumer staples giant to halt its 10-year profit-growth streak with a 2% dip this year, before picking back up with a 9% gain next year.
The stock is shaping a flat base with a 71.66 buy point.
Colgate's Q2 results are due Thursday.
Home Depot ( HD ), with a 2.1% yield, rounds out the five.
The home improvement retailer, which on Thursday said that it's buying Interline Brands in an all-cash deal over $1.6 billion, grew annual profit at least 22% in each of the past five years.
It's seen slowing a bit to 14% this year and the next.
The stock is building a flat base with a 118.09 entry.
Note: The Dividend Leaders table shows only the top 17 results, based on annual yield.
